Section.Description: Environmental effects of this chemical, provided by the International Labour Organization's (ILO's) International Chemical Safety Cards (ICSC).

StringWithMarkup.String: The substance is toxic to aquatic organisms. This substance does enter the environment under normal use. Great care, however, should be taken to avoid any additional release, for example through inappropriate disposal.

Section.Description: This section summarizes the environmental fate/exposure of this chemical, including the natural and artificial sources of the chemical as a pollutant, its environmental fate, biodegradation, abiotic degradation, bioconcentration, etc.

StringWithMarkup.String: Atrazine's production may result in its release to the environment through various waste streams; it's use as a pre- and post-emergence herbicide will result in its direct release to the environment. If released to air, a vapor pressure of 2.89X10-7 mm Hg at 25 °C indicates atrazine will exist in both the vapor and particulate phases in the atmosphere. Vapor-phase atrazine will be degraded in the atmosphere by reaction with photochemically-produced hydroxyl radicals; the half-life for this reaction in air is estimated to be 14 hours. Particulate-phase atrazine will be removed from the atmosphere by wet or dry deposition. If released to soil, atrazine is expected to have very high to slight mobility based on Koc values of 26-1164. Volatilization half-lives of atrazine from soil have been reported as 111 to >1000 days. Degradation half-lives of atrazine were 1.4 to 108 days in soils at varying temperatures and moisture content. In soils, hydrolysis of atrazine is favored by low soil pH, high organic matter content, low moisture content, high temperature, and high clay content. If released into water, atrazine is expected to adsorb to suspended solids and sediment based upon the reported Koc values. Atrazine was degraded by 23% in raw seawater after 96 hours. However, atrazine was found to be recalcitrant in natural groundwater after a period of 96 days. The half-life of atrazine in an anaerobic wetland sediment was determined to be 224 days with no additional carbon present; the only metabolite present during degradation was hydroxyatrazine. Atrazine may undergo photolysis in sunlit surface waters. Volatilization from water surfaces is not expected based on a Henry's Law constant of 2.6X10-9 atm-cu m/mol. Reported BCFs in fish of <0.27-96.0 suggest bioconcentration in aquatic organisms is low to moderate. Occupational exposure to atrazine may occur through inhalation and dermal contact with this compound at workplaces where atrazine is produced or used. Monitoring data indicate that the general population may be exposed to atrazine via inhalation of ambient air, or ingestion of food and drinking water. Regional exposure may also occur to the general population downwind of application operations due to particulate transport. (SRC)

StringWithMarkup.String: TERRESTRIAL FATE: Based on a classification scheme(1), Koc values of atrazine ranging from 26 to 1164(2-4) indicate that atrazine is expected to have high to slight mobility in soil. Volatilization half-lives of atrazine in soil range from 111 to >1000 days(5). Biodegradation of atrazine in soil is affected by the moisture content of the soil, the half-life of atrazine at 25 °C in wet (and dry) Colorado loam soil, New York sandy loam soil, and Mississippi silt loam was determined to be 30 (90), 28 (55), and 35 (78) days, respectively(6). Temperature and pH also affect the biodegradation of atrazine in soil. Microbial degradation of atrazine in silty loam and sand samples occurred in alkaline soil with the primary metabolites of desethyl atrazine and deisopropylatrazine while chemical degradation of atrazine yielded hydroxyatrazine; in addition, atrazine degraded 3-4 times faster in soils at 25 °C than at 10 °C(7).

Reference: (1) Ma L, Selim HM; Rev Environ Contam Toxicol 145: 129-73 (1996)
(2) Li GC, Felbeck GT; Soil Sci 114: 201-8 (1972)
(3) Armstrong DE et al; Soil Science Soc Amer Proc 31: 61-6 (1967)
(4) Khan SU; Pest Sci 9: 39-43 (1978)
(5) Jones TW et al; J Environ Qual 11: 632-8 (1982)
(6) Arthur EL et al; in The Lysimeter Concept: Environmental Behavior or Pesticides, Fuhr F et al, eds., Washington, DC: Amer Chem Soc, chapt 7 pp 88-114 (1998)

StringWithMarkup.String: TERRESTRIAL FATE: Chemical degradation of atrazine may be more important environmentally than biodegradation in soil. In soils, hydrolysis of atrazine is favored by low soil pH, high organic matter content, low moisture content, high temperature, and high clay content(1). Atrazine may hydrolyze in either acidic or basic soils yet is fairly resistant to hydrolysis at neutral pHs(2). The rate of hydrolysis was found to drastically increase upon small additions of humic materials, indicating atrazine hydrolysis could be catalyzed; the half-life of atrazine at 25 °C and pH of 4 was 244 days without an additive and 1.73 days with the presence of 2% humic acid(2). At 25 °C, a 5 mg/L solution of fulvic acid at pHs of 2.9, 4.5, 6.0 and 7.0 resulted in half-lives of 34.8, 174, 398 and 742 days, respectively(2). Hydrolysis of atrazine followed first order kinetics producing hydroxyatrazine as the transformation product(3-4). Atrazine has the potential to photolyze from surface soils(5). The half-lives for sunlight exposed ring-labeled atrazine at concentration of 0.10 ppm under aerobic conditions were 330 and 385 days for two agricultural soils(5). In a 12 week study with intact soil columns from a field with no previous pesticide history (Ames, IA), 77% of (14)C radio-labeled atrazine was reported as remaining in the top 10 cm with 1.2% reported as leachate(6). Of the 77% in the top 10 cm, 57% was unextractable residue, 3.6% was the degradate desethyl atrazine, other degradates were present at lesser amounts(6).

Reference: (1) Webb RMT et al; Environ Toxicol Chem 30: 1973-81 (2011)

StringWithMarkup.String: AQUATIC FATE: Based on a classification scheme(1), Koc values of atrazine ranging from 26 to 1164(2-4) indicate that atrazine is expected to adsorb to suspended solids and sediment in water(SRC). Atrazine is not expected to volatilize from water surfaces(5) based on a Henry's Law constant of 2.6X10-9 atm-cu m/mol(6). According to a classification scheme(7), a BCF range from <0.27(8) to 96.0 (9) in fish suggests bioconcentration in aquatic organisms is low to moderate(SRC). Atrazine was degraded by 23% in raw seawater after 96 hours(10). Atrazine was found to be recalcitrant in natural groundwater after a period of 96 days; no transformation of atrazine was observed after 74 and 96 days in simulated groundwater laboratory experiments(11). The half-life of atrazine in an anaerobic wetland sediment was determined to be 224 days with no additional carbon present; the only metabolite present during degradation was hydroxyatrazine(12). Hydrolysis occurs slowly under neutral conditions but may be more important under acidic or alkaline environments based on hydrolysis half-lives of 240 and 100 days at pH 4 and 11, respectively(13). The hydrolysis half-life of atrazine at 25 °C and pH of 4 was 244 days without an additive and 1.73 days with the presence of 2% humic acid(14). Alkaline hydrolysis proceeds twice as rapidly as acidic hydrolysis(15). Photolysis in surface waters may occur slowly based upon a photolysis half-life of 335 days when aqueous solutions of atrazine were exposed to natural sunlight(16).

Reference: (1) Bidleman TF; Environ Sci Technol 22: 361-367 (1988)
(2) MacBean C, ed; e-Pesticide Manual. 15th ed., ver. 5.1, Alton, UK; British Crop Protection Council. Atrazine (1912-24-9) (2008-2010)
(3) US EPA; Estimation Program Interface (EPI) Suite. Ver. 4.1. Nov, 2012. Available from, as of Oct 23, 2017: https://www2.epa.gov/tsca-screening-tools
(4) Thurman EM et al; in Preprints of Papers Presented at the 209th ACS Natl Mtg. Anaheim, CA, April 2-7 35: 286-87 (1995)

StringWithMarkup.String: ATMOSPHERIC FATE: According to a model of gas/particle partitioning of semivolatile organic compounds in the atmosphere(1), atrazine, which has a vapor pressure of 2.89X10-7 mm Hg at 25 °C(2), will exist in both the vapor and particulate phases in the ambient atmosphere. Vapor-phase atrazine is degraded in the atmosphere by reaction with photochemically-produced hydroxyl radicals(SRC); the half-life for this reaction in air is estimated to be 14 hours(SRC), estimated from its rate constant of 2.7X10-11 cu cm/molecule-sec at 25 °C(SRC) that was derived using a structure estimation method(3). Particulate-phase atrazine may be removed from the air by wet or dry deposition(SRC). Atrazine has been detected as far away as 100 to 300 kilometers (62 to 186 miles) from the nearest treated corn field, indicating long-range transport in the atmosphere(4).

Section.Description: This section provides information on environmental biodegradation for this compound. Biodegradation is the breakdown of organic matter by microorganisms, such as bacteria and fungi.  An important measure of biodegradability of wastewater is the biochemical oxygen demand (BOD), which is the amount of dissolved oxygen (DO) needed (i.e. demanded) by aerobic biological organisms to break down organic material present in a given water sample at certain temperature over a specific time period.

Reference: (1) Walker A; Rev Weed Sci 3: 1-17 (1987)
(2) Anderson TA et al Chemosphere 28: 1551-57 (1994

StringWithMarkup.String: AEROBIC: The half-life of atrazine at 25 °C in wet (and dry) Colorado loam soil, New York sandy loam soil, and Mississippi silt loam was determined to be 30 (90), 28 (55), and 35 (78) days respectively(1). The percent atrazine remaining from rhizosphere and edaphosphere (non-vegetated) soil samples collected at an agrochemicals dealership in Iowa was determined to be approximately 55% in the rhizosphere and 75% in the edaphosphere, suggesting that the microbial activity of Kochia sp in the rhizosphere soil increased atrazine degradation(2). Atrazine was found to exhibit a half-life of about 30 days in soil samples collected from the top surface (10 cm) from the Ebro delta, Tarragona, Spain between 1989 and 1991; deethyl atrazine was the major degradate formed, with deisopropylatrazine detected in one sample(3). Degradation studies of atrazine in subsoils from an Atlantic coastal plain watershed revealed 13.3 to 25.0% carbon dioxide evolution from sandy loam soils, indicating that atrazine was not appreciably mineralized in the soils(4). In a study using a Port Byron silt loam soil (pH 5.4), 68% of the applied radio-labeled atrazine was present 16 months after treatment; hydroxyatrazine was the major degradation product(5). Atrazine had half-lives of 20-360 days, observed in laboratory studies conducted with loamy soil from a corn field in Bologna, Italy(6). The shortest half-lives were observed for soils inoculated at temperatures of 35 °C, while the longest half-lives observed occurred at 5 °C(7). Experiments with s-triazine-adapted Colorado soil (35.2% sand, 28% silt, 36.8% clay, 19 g C/kg organic matter and pH 7.9) had atrazine degradation half-lives of 2.0 to 28.2 days(7). Experiments with s-triazine-adapted Mississippi soil (15.8% sand, 47.2% silt, 36.7% clay, 13 g C/Kg organic matter and pH 6.67) had atrazine degradation half-lives of 0.8 to 5.6 days(7). The biodegradation half-life of atrazine in adapted surface soil was 5-18 days, half-lives increased with soil depth to 43 days at 80-110 cm depth, in unadapted soils surface half-lives were 56-72 days and 156-186 days in subsurface unadapted soils; studies were conducted in Northern Greece(8).

StringWithMarkup.String: AEROBIC: Atrazine was degraded 23% in 96 hours when incubated in raw seawater obtained from the Pacific Ocean(1). Atrazine had half-lives of 340-7900 and 19-120 hours in unexposed and re-exposed sediment/water samples, respectively, collected from Lake Superior, Superior Harbor and St. Louis River(2). Microorganisms in aerobic incubations of alluvial aquifer sediment mineralized <0.1-1.5% of added radio-labeled atrazine; carbon dioxide production was greater in shallow sediment (<6 m) than in deep sediment (>17 m)(3). Atrazine degradation in silty loam and sand samples collected from Hesse, Germany was investigated; microbial degradation of atrazine occurred in alkaline soil with the primary metabolites of desethyl atrazine and deisopropylatrazine while chemical degradation of atrazine yielded hydroxyatrazine; in addition, atrazine degraded 3-4 times faster in soils at 25 °C than at 10 °C(4). Measures of CO2 evolution from atrazine labeled with (14)C at the ethyl or propyl groupings(5) have demonstrated that dealkylation is the major mechanism involved in microbial degradation of atrazine(6-7). Decomposition studies of (14)C ring labeled atrazine evolve (14)CO2 at slow rates, indicating the s-triazine ring is fairly resistant to microbial degradation(5-7). Aerobic half-lives of atrazine in wetland samples from Columbus, OH region ranged from 4.6 to 1734 days, dependent on location and depth of sample(8).

Reference: (1) Agertved J et al; Ground Water 30: 500-06 (1992)
(2) Klint M et al; J Environ Qual 22: 262-66 (1993)

StringWithMarkup.String: AEROBIC: Atrazine was found to be recalcitrant in groundwater after a period of 96 days; no transformation of atrazine was observed after 74 and 96 days in simulated groundwater laboratory experiments(1). The potential for biodegradation of atrazine in an aerobic aquifer was investigated in laboratory batch experiments; atrazine was not degraded during an incubation period of 539 days in groundwater and 174 days in suspensions of groundwater/aquifer sediment; in a microcosm experiment, atrazine was degraded from 100 ug/L to 50 ug/L in 30 days, no further degradation was observed after the 30 days(2). The biodegradation of atrazine in groundwater samples collected from an agricultural area in southern France was investigated over 180 days; after a lag period of 15 to 44 days, catabolism occurred rapidly and total degradation of added atrazine occurred in 21 to 70 days(3).

Reference: (1) Blume E et al; J Agric Food Chem 52: 7382-8 (2004)

StringWithMarkup.String: AEROBIC: The biodegradation of atrazine was tested in soil from three different field locations near Piketon, OH. The percentage of sand, silt, and clay varied from 8 to 22, 44 to 56, and 34 to 42, respectively. The pH increased with depth, ranging from 6.58 to 7.76; total organic carbon, nitrogen, and phosphorus, decreased with depth(1).

StringWithMarkup.String: The rate constant for the vapor-phase reaction of atrazine with photochemically-produced hydroxyl radicals has been estimated as 2.7X10-11 cu cm/molecule-sec at 25 °C(SRC) using a structure estimation method(1). This corresponds to an atmospheric half-life of about 14 hours at an atmospheric concentration of 5X10+5 hydroxyl radicals per cu cm(1). Atrazine exposed to UV light (275-watt sun-lamps) for 48 hours was determined to be 8% degraded in aqueous solution (half-life of 346 hours); atrazine photolysis was not detected on air-dried silty clay loam and air-dried sand(2). The photolytic rate constant and half-life in Isar River water under sunlight irradiation were 2.8X10+5/sec and 7.3 hours, respectively; in distilled water the values were 2.3X10+4/sec and 21.3 hours(3). The aqueous photolysis half-life of atrazine at pH 7 in natural light and using a mercury lamp was 335 days and 17.5 hours, respectively; the soil photolysis half-life of atrazine in natural light, using a mercury lamp, and using a xenon lamp was 12 days, 5 days, and 45 days, respectively(4).

StringWithMarkup.String: Atrazine was completely hydrolyzed within 3-4 days at extreme pHs(1). The hydrolysis half-lives of atrazine in aqueous buffered systems at 25 °C and pHs of 1, 2, 3, 4, 11, 12, and 13 were determined to be 3.3, 14, 58, 240, 100, 12.5 and 1.5 days, respectively(2). At a pH of 6.97 and 25 °C the half-life of atrazine was determined to be 1800 years in the absence of any acid, base or buffer catalysts, based on a pseudo-first-order rate constant of 1.24X10-11/sec(3). Alkaline hydrolysis proceeds twice as rapid as acidic hydrolysis(4). The rate of hydrolysis was found to drastically increase upon small additions of sterilized soil(5), humic acid(6), and fulvic acid(7), indicating atrazine hydrolysis could be catalyzed(5-7). For example the half-life of atrazine at 25 °C and pH of 4 was 244 days without an additive and 1.73 days with the presence of 2% humic acid(6). At 25 °C, a 5 mg/L solution of fulvic acid, which naturally occurs in soils and many surface waters(8), and at pHs of 2.9, 4.5, 6.0 and 7.0 maintained half-lives of 34.8, 174, 398 and 742 days, respectively(7). Hydrolysis of atrazine followed first-order kinetics producing hydroxyatrazine as the transformation product(5-7). Atrazine had a hydrolytic half-life of 225 days at pH 4, 15 °C in the dark(9). In artificial light, atrazine had abiotic half-lives of 17-34, 19-155 and 40 days in pH 4, pH 7 and buffered Upland water, respectively(9). No degradation was evident in Thames water at pH 8.2 or Upland water at pH 6.4(9). The hydrolysis half-life for atrazine was 9.6-168 days in slurries of a mineralized soil(10).

StringWithMarkup.String: At wavelengths greater than or equal to 290 nm, the photolysis half-life of atrazine at a concentration of 10 mg/L in aqueous solution at 15 °C was 25 hr as compared to a half-life of 4.9 hr for identical conditions with acetone added as a sensitizer at a concentration of 1 mL/100 mL(1). After 135 min exposure to 300 nm at 50 °C, 8% of a 30 ppm aqueous solution of atrazine was lost to photolysis, whereas 6 and 17% was lost from similar solutions with 0.2% of two respective surface active agents(2). Fulvic acid was found to increase the photostability of atrazine in aqueous solution and the photolytic half-life of atrazine in fulvic acid solution increased with decreasing pH(3). At wavelengths >290 nm nitrate and nitrite ions can yield hydroxyl radicals which can react with atrazine(4). However, atrazine did not react with singlet oxygen in water(5). The primary photo-transformation products of atrazine: two de-alkyl-, de-N,N'-dialkyl and the hydroxyl- analogs of atrazine in the presence of acetone used as a photosensitizer(1), hydroxyatrazine and three N-dealkylated products in the presence of fulvic acid(4), and de-ethylated atrazine and 2-chloro-4-(isopropylamino)-6-acetaamido-5-triazine in dye sensitized solution(6). Atrazine was photodegraded 51-80% over a two day period in surface water collected May, July and Oct 2010 from the Columbia Basin, Washington(7).

Reference: (1) Albanis TA et al; Toxicol Environ Chem 19: 171-78 (1989)
(2) Gamble DS, Khan SU; Can J Chem 66: 2605-17 (1988)

StringWithMarkup.String: The amount of atrazine hydrolyzed from an aqueous suspension of sandy clay loam soil from initial concentrations of 1, 2, 6, 10, and 14 ug/mL were determined to be 0.2, 0.4, 1.4, 2.3, and 3.2 ug/L; the amount of atrazine hydrolyzed in the presence of 0.20% fly ash was determined to be 0.4, 0.7, 2.3, 3.5, and 5.1 ug/L(1). Atrazine hydrolysis in aqueous suspensions of humic acid at 25 °C resulted in a rate constant of 1.8X10-1/day(2). The pH of soil or water system has the greatest effect on hydrolysis of atrazine, with acidic pH levels promoting atrazine hydrolysis to hydroxyatrazine; at pH >7 the first-order rate coefficients in water are more than 1000 times slower than at pH 2(3). The hydrolysis rate in water also increased when concentrations of dissolved organic carbon in the system increased and temperature increased(3). Abiotic hydrolysis of atrazine in natural waters yielded base-hydrolysis product hydroxyatrazine(4). The first-order rate constant for hydrolysis of atrazine in well water at temperatures of 4 and 30 °C and stored 19 weeks ranged from -2.4X10-3/week to -3.7X10-3/week; assuming no lag-phase, the half-life of atrazine was estimated at 4.5 years in groundwater(5). In soils, hydrolysis of atrazine is favored by low soil pH, high organic matter content, low moisture content, high temperature, and high clay content(6).

Section.Description: This section provides information on environmental bioconcentration for this compound.  Bioconcentration is the accumulation of a chemical in or on an organism when the source of chemical is solely water. Bioconcentration is a term that was created for use in the field of aquatic toxicology. Bioconcentration can also be defined as the process by which a chemical concentration in an aquatic organism exceeds that in water as a result of exposure to a waterborne chemical.

Section.Description: Sorption to soils and sediments is an important factor on the transport and fate of organic contaminants in the environment.  The soil/water adsorption coefficient, also known as solid-water distribution coefficient (Kd), measures the amount of chemical substance adsorbed onto soil per amount of water.  Since adsorption occurs predominantly by partition into the soil organic matter, it is more useful to normalize the Kd value to the organic carbon content of a soil and express the distribution coefficient in Koc (organic carbon normalized distribution coefficient).  The greater the Kd (or Koc) value, the less likely a chemical will leach or contribute to runoff.  A very high value means it is strongly adsorbed onto soil and organic matter and does not move throughout the soil.

StringWithMarkup.String: The Koc of atrazine in loamy soil, calcareous clay, and high clay was determined to be 109.9, 80.0, and 88.9, respectively(1). The Koc values for atrazine in four Hawaii soils were 54-150 mL/g(2). The Koc of atrazine in a Zimmerman fine sand, a Verndale sandy loam and a Waukegan silt loam, each with 9.6% water content, was determined to be 1164, 775 and 936, respectively(3). The Koc of atrazine in Norfolk, Rion, Cape Fear and Webster soils was determined to be 150-200, 84, 202, and 166, respectively(4). Atrazine had a reported mean Koc of 126.9 (range of 26 to 821) in 101 allophanic and non-allophanic surface soil samples collected throughout New Zealand(5). Koc values of atrazine for three regions of Argentina were reported as 77-161(6). Koc values of two soils from Reunion Island, France were reported as 97 and 117(7). Atrazine had measured Koc values of 88 in vegetated filter strip soil (37.9% sand, 31.9% silt, 30.2% clay, 4.2% organic carbon, pH 7.6) and 92 in cultivated soil (36.8% sand, 29.5% silt, 33.7% clay, 2.5% organic carbon, pH 7.6)(8). According to a classification scheme(9), these Koc values suggest that atrazine is expected to have very high to slight mobility in soil, depending upon soil type(SRC). The Koc range for atrazine in salt marsh sediment was 64-546.3, with 59.2-91.8% of atrazine adsorbed to sediment(10).

StringWithMarkup.String: The rate constant for sorption and desorption of atrazine by organic soil at 25 °C was determined to be 5.02X10-2/day (half-life = 13.8 days) for sorption and 0.1507/day (half-life = 4.6 days) for desorption(1). Atrazine sorption half-life ranged from 3.6 to 735 days and desorption half-life ranged from 1 to 11 days in slurries of a mineralized soil(2). An addition of fly ash up to 0.5% in a sandy clay loam results in decreased adsorption of atrazine by 7.3% on the avg; the same amount of fly ash in clay soil decreases atrazine adsorption by 6.5%(3). The adsorption of atrazine by aluminum montmorillonite was 0.37 mole/g at pH 6.0, by aluminum montmorillonite + sodium hydroxide was 2.70 mole/g at pH 7.4, and by aluminum hydroxide was 0.50 mole/g at pH 6.2; the adsorption of atrazine by iron montmorillonite was 0.94 mole/g at pH 4.6, by iron montmorillonite + sodium hydroxide was 1.50 mole/g at pH 5.7, and by iron hydroxide was 0.32 mole/g at pH 7.5(4). At an initial concentration of 100 ug/L atrazine, the amount of atrazine adsorbed by montmorillonite at pH 4.5 and pH 9.5 was determined to be 4.4 and 1.65 ug/L, respectively; the amount of atrazine adsorbed by kaolinite at pH 4.5 and pH 9.5 was determined to be 0.02 and 0.03 ug/L, respectively(5). The rate constant for the adsorption of atrazine on humic acid at 20 °C and pH 2.5 to 6.2 ranged from 1.8X10-5 to 7.2X10-1; the amount of atrazine adsorbed by humic acid within 24 hours decreased with increase in pH with no adsorption observed above pH 5.5(6). Atrazine adsorption is higher at lower soil pH and reaches maximum adsorption when surface acidity is approximately equal to the dissociation constant; soil organic matter has the highest adsorption affinity to atrazine among soil constituents: in a study of a Webster soil, organic matter contributed to 68% of atrazine adsorption(7). In a soil column study, the presence of colloids enhanced the transport of atrazine by 2 to 18%, depending upon colloid type and mobility; colloids with higher pH, total exchangeable bases, cation-exchange capacity, organic carbon, surface area, and electrophoretic mobility showed greater mobility, greater affinity for atrazine, and greater potential to co-transport atrazine; in contrast, increased levels of kaolinite, iron, and aluminum inhibited atrazine adsorption and transport(8). In fields with varying ground covers (bare ground, orchard grass, tall fescue, timothy, smooth bromegrass, switch grass) treated with atrazine, leach concentrations ranged from 2.52 to 5.87% of applied amount over 25 days with six rain events(9).

StringWithMarkup.String: The Henry's Law constant for atrazine is 2.6X10-9 atm-cu m/mole(1). This Henry's Law constant indicates that atrazine is expected to be essentially nonvolatile from moist soil and water surfaces(2). Atrazine is not expected to volatilize from dry soil surfaces(SRC) based on a vapor pressure of 2.89X10-7 mm Hg(3). The volatilization half-life of atrazine from soil surfaces was determined to range from 111 to >1000 days depending upon soil type, soil moisture, and temperature; the volatilization half-life from oat leaves was 14.5-62.2 days(4). The time required for 50% of the initial application of atrazine to volatilize following application to soil was determined to be 500 days(5). The avg daily percent disappearance of atrazine from conventional-till and no-till surface soils (at least 30% of the soil surface is covered by plant residue) in the field due to volatilization was determined to be 2.7% and 0.9-3.2%, respectively(6).

StringWithMarkup.String: GROUNDWATER: Atrazine was identified in 30 of 2208 California well water samples collected between July 1994 to June 1995 at 0.05-0.7 ppb(1). Groundwater samples collected from 183 existing production wells throughout the San Joaquin Valley, CA, from 1985-1987 were found to contain atrazine residue at 0.1-0.4 ug/L(2). Water samples from 240 private wells in rural Illinois collected over a one year period detected atrazine 11 times with an avg concentration of 0.15 ug/L(3). In a national pesticide survey conducted by the EPA, the estimated number of community water system wells containing atrazine was determined to be 1570 (1.7%); the estimated number of rural domestic wells containing atrazine was determined to be 70,800 (0.7%)(4). The concentration of atrazine in alluvial aquifer well water samples collected from 30 different wells in Denver, CO was determined to have a max of 0.21 ug/L (approximately 42% frequency detection)(5). In ground water samples collected June-Aug 1998 from Cedar River alluvial aquifer, Cedar Rapids, IA, atrazine was reported at <0.05-1.39 ug/L(6). Atrazine was detected in 8 of 18 row crop, 10 of 20 orchard and 13 of 34 public supply groundwater wells sampled 1993 to 1995 from the Central Columbia Plateau, WA(7). Atrazine was also detected in 10 of 18 row crop, 11 of 20 orchard and 14 of 34 public supply groundwater wells when the same wells were tested again 2002 to 2003, detection limits varied and were not reported as this was a trend study(7). Atrazine was detected in 22.4% of 303 groundwater wells sampled during 1991 to 1994 from the Midwestern Reconnaissance Network, the max concentration was 2.09 ug/L(8). In corn producing regions of Nebraska, atrazine was found in ground water at 200-800 ng/L(9). The concentration of atrazine in 14 irrigation wells in central Nebraska was 0.06-3.12 ug/L(10). Atrazine was detected in 30% of 2460 groundwater samples analyzed during 1992 to 1996 from 20 of the largest hydrologic watersheds in the US at a maximum concentration of 4.2 ug/L(11). Atrazine was reported at 0.00-0.66 ug/L in 15 ground water samples collected from Mid Atlantic, South Atlantic Coast, Great Lakes, Ohio, Upper and Lower Mississippi, Missouri, Arkansas-White-Red and Texas-Gulf watersheds in a two year study (2003-2004)(12). A study of 86 wells across Iowa reported atrazine in 16.3% of the samples with a maximum concentration of 0.38 ug/L(13). Atrazine was detected in 19% of 655 water samples from groundwater in 303 Midwestern US wells collected 1992-1993(14).

StringWithMarkup.String: DRINKING WATER: The seven day avg concentration of atrazine in three New Orleans, LA drinking water supplies, collected Aug 1974, ranged from 4.9 to 5.4 ug/L(1). In a study conducted in California from 1975-1991, atrazine was detected in 126 of 921 groundwater drinking wells, at a maximum concentration of 10 ug/L(2). Atrazine was measured in drinking water sources in 15 geographic districts in Kentucky at mean levels of 0.21-1.39 ug/L(3). Atrazine had a time-weighted annual mean of 0.72, 0.83 and 1.72 ppb in 1995, 1996 and 1997, respectively, in finished water from Higginsville City Lake, MO(4). Atrazine was reported at 0.00 to 5.70 ug/L in 356 drinking water taken from Mid Atlantic, South Atlantic Coast, Great Lakes, Ohio, Upper and Lower Mississippi, Missouri, Arkansas-White-Red and Texas-Gulf watersheds in a two year study (2003-2004)(5). Atrazine was detected in finished water at 15 of 18 drinking water treatment plants across the US in samples taken 2006 and 2007 at a maximum concentration of 870 ng/L and a median of 49 ng/L(6). Atrazine was detected in finished water samples collected Dec 2009 to Dec 2010 from a plant in southeast US at 0.6-14.8 ng/L(7). The concentration of atrazine in drinking water in a study conducted 1991-1993 in Belgium ranged from 0.1 ppb to 0.005 ppm(8). In 33 drinking water supplies in Sweden sampled 1992-1994, atrazine concentrations were reported as not detected to 0.3 ug/L(9). Forty drinking water samples collected from December 1992 to February 1993 at the treatment plants of Athens, Greece; atrazine/simazine was detected at a mean concentration range of 0.040-0.045 ug/L(10). Atrazine was detected at concentrations >0.1 ug/L in numerous drinking water samples collected from five water companies in England in 1993(11).

StringWithMarkup.String: The remove efficiency of atrazine by pre-ozonation/flocculation/sedimentation, intermediate ozonation and filtration/chlorination was 39.6, 43.0 and 45.9% respectively in a drinking water treatment plant located in the southeast US; the overall removal efficiency of atrazine was 70.4%(1). Atrazine was detected in leachate samples from 2 of 22 landfill effluents collected 2011 and 2012 from sites in 12 US states at a median concentration of 466 ng/L(2). In effluent samples collected Mar 23 to Oct 29, 2015 from a wastewater treatment plant in Minnesota, atrazine was detected at 8.1-22 ng/L(3). Atrazine was detected in raw sludge and treated sludge at unreported concentrations in samples taken from 37 water pollution control plants in Ontario, Canada between January and July 1986(4). Atrazine was detected in 68% of effluent samples collected from 90 European wastewater treatment plants at <1-36.6 ng/L (average 4.2 ng/L, median 2.2 ng/L); samples were collected 2010(5). The average concentration of atrazine in a streamlet flowing through a golf course in Shiga Prefecture, Japan, sampled once a week for 1 year during runoff events, was determined to be 0.28 ug/L; atrazine was not listed on the on-site inventory  of turf chemicals applied(6). Atrazine was detected at two of three roof runoff sample locations in Gdansk, Poland at concentrations of 0.25 to 0.58 ng/L, sample dates were March to May 2000(7).

Reference: (1) Shipitalo MJ, Owens LB; Environ Sci Technol 37: 944-50 (2003)

StringWithMarkup.String: In a six year study (1995-2000) of crops grown in Coshocton, OH, the concentration of atrazine was highest when runoff occurred shortly after application and declined sharply with time. Atrazine degradation products (deethylatrazine and deisoprpylatrazine) runoff concentrations started low and peaked about 25 days after application(1).

StringWithMarkup.String: SEDIMENT: The concentration of atrazine in the sediment of the German Wadden Sea ranged from not detected to 50 ng/kg(1). Atrazine concentrations in sediments collected from the Danube and Traun Rivers in Austria were 0.44-0.64 ug/kg(2). StringWithMarkup.String: SOIL: In a study conducted from Jan to Sept 1989, the concentration of atrazine in soil samples collected from selected agricultural areas near Havre, Ronan, and Huntley, MT ranged from <0.1 to 82 ug/kg(1). In the Bangkok area of Thailand, atrazine was detected in the soil of onion fields at 9.66 and 4.5 ug/kg(2). Atrazine was detected in agricultural soils collected from southern areas of Poland at 0.69 to 19.59 ug/g(3). Soil samples taken across Canadian agricultural areas reported atrazine concentrations of 32.2 and 0.99 ng/g in samples collected from St. Anicet and Baie St. Francis in 2005(4). Atrazine was not detected (detection limit 0.3 ng/g) in Abbotsford, Bratt's Lake, Egbert, Downsview, or Kensington in 2005(4). Atrazine was not detected (detection limit 0.11 ng/g) in 35 soil samples collected June 2010 from farmland locations in Shenyang, China(5).

StringWithMarkup.String: URBAN/SUBURBAN: Atrazine was not identified in the gas phase, but was identified in the particulate phase in 7 out of 24 samples of urban air collected in Mississippi at a maximum concentration of 0.019 ng/cu m(1). Atrazine was detected in the vapor phase in 9 out of 21 samples at a max concentration of 2.6 ng/cu m, and in the particulate phase in 14 out of 21 samples at a maximum concentration of 0.42 ng/cu m, samples were collected from agricultural areas of Mississippi(1). Atrazine was not detected (detection limit not reported) in air samples collected Oct 1996 to Sept 1997 from Iowa City(2). Air samples collected once a week from April 18 to Dec 19, 2000, near the Choptank River in Cambridge, MD had reported atrazine concentrations of 55 to 1600 pg/cu m in 94% of the samples(3). Atrazine was analyzed in 1991 in the air and in the total atmospheric fallout (dry and wet depositions) in the Paris region; the maximum atrazine concentration in the wet depostion was 350 ug/L, the concentration of atrazine in the air was close to the detection limit of 0.03 ng/cu m(4). Atrazine was detected at 0.20-0.32 ng/cu m in ambient air samples from Kitakyushu City, Japan collected July 1991 and April 1992(5). Atrazine was reported in atmospheric samples from Strasbourg, France at 690-51,260 pg/cu m, samples were collected June and July 1994(6).

StringWithMarkup.String: RURAL REMOTE: In samples collected Aug 1994 to Oct 1995 from Sleeping Bear Dunes, MI, atrazine was reported at 0.4-71 pg/cu m with a mean concentration of 11 pg/cu m(1). Atrazine was detected at a maximum of 0.14 ug/cu m at a farm location outside of Iowa City in samples collected Jun 1997, and not detected the other 11 months from Oct 1996 to Sept 1997(2). Atrazine was detected at a maximum of 0.014 ug/cu m at a remote park (Macbride) outside of Iowa City in samples collected Aug 1997, and not detected the other 11 months from Oct 1996 to Sept 1997(2). Atrazine was reported in atmospheric samples from Aubure and Colmar, France at a range of not detected to 1400 and 640-5970 pg/cu m, samples were collected April to July 1994(3). Atrazine was detected in 12% of the samples collected from four locations in Saskatchewan, Canada, at a mean concentration of 0.02 ng/cu m and maximum concentration of 0.26 ng/cu m(5).

StringWithMarkup.String: RURAL/REMOTE: Air samples collected across Canadian agricultural area reported atrazine concentrations as <1.8-44.0, 79.0-800, <1.8-598, 140-431 and <1.8-1490 pg/cu m in air samples collected in Abbotsford, Egbert, Vineland, St. Anicet and Baie St. Francis, respectively, in 2004. StringWithMarkup.String: In a ten-year study of ready-to-eat foods conducted between 1982 and 1991, atrazine was determined to have an avg concentration of 0.004 ug/g(1). Atrazine was detected at unreported concentrations as a residue in foods (49,877 samples) collected between 1978 and 1982 in the United States(2). Atrazine was detected at unreported concentrations as a residue in domestic and imported foods (49,055 samples) collected between 1983 and 1986 in the United States(3). Atrazine was detected at unreported concentrations as a residue in foods (27,065 samples) collected between 1988 and 1989 in the United States(4). Atrazine was not detected (detection limit 4 ug/g) in fresh peaches harvested Aug 5, 2000 from a field near Skydra, Greece or in canned halves peaches produced July to Sept 1999(5). Atrazine was not detected (detection limit 1 ug/kg) in eight olive (Olea europaea) oil samples collected in Spain(6). In a market basket survey of approximately 280 food types (731 samples) collected on eight occasions from Oct 2003 to Aug 2005 from grocery stores across the US, atrazine was detected once at trace levels (approx 0.13 ppb) in fresh/frozen green beans(7).

StringWithMarkup.String: The average concentration of atrazine in rooted aquatic Hydrilla verticillata plant tissues exposed to 0.057 mg/L solution of atrazine was determined to be 3.25 ug/g tissue in the root and 7.56 ug/g tissue in the shoot(1). The concentration of atrazine in barley (Hordeum vulgare) exposed to an initial concentration of 2 ppm atrazine was determined to be 2.53 ppm; 59.5% was metabolized, 48.9% of the metabolites were polar and 10.6% were insoluble(2). Atrazine was detected in grass and cereal crops collected from southern areas of Poland at 7.85-23.85 and 1.88-43.08 ug/g, respectively, sampling dates were not reported(3).

Atrazine was analyzed for but not detected in carp (Cyprinus carpio) from the Llobregat River near Barcelona, Spain(2). StringWithMarkup.String: Atrazine was detected in dry deposition samples collected at a farm location outside of Iowa City, in Iowa City, at a remote park (Macbride) outside of Iowa City, and at Oakdale (University of Iowa) at concentrations of 0.1-0.25, 0.13, 0.11-0.12, and 0.1-0.19 ug, respectively, in samples collected May 1997(1). Atrazine was reported as 4.6 to 31.0 ug/sq m in six settled dust samples taken from homes in Cortland and Tompkins Counties, NY in 1999(2). Surface dust wipe samples had atrazine concentrations of 2.1-76.1 ug/sq m in 6 of 6 first visit samples and 6.8-92.6 ug/sq m in 8 of 9 second visit samples(2). Carpet dust samples tested positive in 7 of 10 samples taken on both first and second visits with atrazine levels of 0.1-20.1 and 0.1-35.3 ug/sq m, respectively(2). Atrazine is listed as an ingredient in home use landscape/yard and pesticide products(3).

StringWithMarkup.String: NIOSH (NOES Survey 1981-1983) has statistically estimated that 1001 workers (123 of these are female) were potentially exposed to atrazine in the US(1). Survey does not include farm workers. Occupational exposure to atrazine may occur through inhalation and dermal contact with this compound at workplaces where atrazine is produced or used(SRC). Atrazine exposure was evaluated in 6 manufacturing workers of an atrazine production plant with total atrazine exposure varying from 10 to 700 umol/workshift(2). Atrazine was detected at 44-199 ng in 12 of 88 hand samples collected from farm children's hands 3 days after application to soil by the father(3). Dermal and respiratory exposure to atrazine associated with mixing-loading, spray gun and boom operation of farm application was determined to be 272 dermal and 12 respiratory ug/kg a.i. during mixing-loading, 54 dermal and 4 respiratory ug/kg a.i. during spray gun operation, and 3 dermal and 11 respiratory ug/kg a.i. during boom operation(4). Monitoring data indicate that the general population may be exposed to atrazine via inhalation of ambient air, ingestion of food and drinking water(SRC). Regional exposure may also occur to the general population downwind of application operations due to particulate transport(SRC). The average concentration of atrazine exposure to persons in Ohio, Illinois, and Iowa via ground and surface waters was determined to be 0.025-0.998 ppb, using monitoring data available in 1990(5).

StringWithMarkup.String: Atrazine was detected in applicator breathing zone air in a study conducted during pesticide application to lawns, trees, and shrubs in urban environments as having a time weighted avg of 0.001 mg/cu m(1). Atrazine was detected in 1 out of 529 urinary samples at a concentration of 1.5 ppb in the National Human Exposure Assessment Survey (NHEXAS) conducted by the Centers for Disease Control (CDC)(2). Atrazine was detected in 2 out of 89 urine samples of children at levels of 0.6 and 22.0 ug/g creatinine during the Minnesota Children's Pesticide Exposure Survey (MNCPES)(3). The metabolite atrazine mercapturate was detected in 2 of 88, 2 of 89 and 2 of 89 in urine samples at days 3, 5 and 7 of monitoring, respectively, in samples taken for the MNCPES(4). Urinary excretion of atrazine in exposed workers of a production plant in Italy revealed maximum excretion rates of 0.1-0.3 ug/hr during the workshift and 0.01-0.04 ug/hr 12 hours after the end of the workshift(5). Atrazine exposure was evaluated in 6 manufacturing workers of an atrazine production plant with total atrazine exposure varying from 10 to 700 umol/workshift; urinary metabolites were comprised of bi-dealkylated (80%), deisopropylated (10%), deethylated (8%), and unmodified atrazine (2%)(6). Atrazine was not detected in human adipose tissue samples collected April 2008 to June 2009 from Nantong, Hexian and Dachang regions of Southeast China(7).
